],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/open#parameters","content":"path:The filesystem path to the collection directory."},"238":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/open-7","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/open","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/open#parameters","content":"option:Runtime settings that control how the collection is accessed."},"239":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/open-8","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/open","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/open#parameters","content":"read_only:Opens the collection in read-only mode. Attempts to write will raise an error."},"240":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/open-9","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/open","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/open#parameters","content":"className: text-base"},"241":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/open-10","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/open","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/open#parameters","content":"type: info"},"242":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/open-11","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/open","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/open#parameters","content":"Use read-only mode when sharing a collection across multiple processes — it ensures safe concurrent access without risking data corruption."},"243":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/open-12","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/open","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/open#parameters","content":"enable_mmap:Uses memory-mapped I/O for faster access (defaults to True). This trades slightly higher memory cache usage for improved performance."},"244":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","type":"page","content":"Optimize","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Working with Data","Collections"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize"},"245":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-0","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"Why Optimization is Needed"},"246":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-1","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#usage-example","content":"Usage Example"},"247":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-2","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#check-indexing-status","content":"Check Indexing Status"},"248":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-3","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#when-to-call-optimize","content":"When to Call optimize()"},"249":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-4","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","content":"The optimize() method improves search performance by building the configured vector index from vectors accumulated in a temporary flat buffer. It runs in the background and does not block reads or writes, ensuring your application remains fully responsive."},"250":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-5","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"In Zvec, newly inserted vectors are not added directly to the configured vector index."},"251":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-6","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"Instead, they are first appended to a lightweight flat (brute-force) index buffer."},"252":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-7","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"This design choice offers important benefits — but also a trade-off:"},"253":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-8","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"✅ Strengths"},"254":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-9","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"Maximum write throughput: Enables high-speed data ingestion."},"255":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-10","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"Streaming inserts: Supports real-time insertion for index types like IVF that don't natively allow incremental updates."},"256":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-11","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"⚠️ Trade-off"},"257":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-12","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"Slower searches over time: As the flat buffer grows, search performance degrades."},"258":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-13","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"🔁 Solution"},"259":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-14","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"Call optimize() periodically. This triggers a background process that merges the buffered vectors into the configured vector index — without interrupting ongoing reads or writes. 🚀"},"260":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-15","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"className: text-base"},"261":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-16","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"type: info"},"262":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-17","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#why-optimization-is-needed","content":"optimize() is a synchronous method (it returns only after the optimization has finished), but it does not lock the collection.Other threads can continue reading, writing, and querying without delay — your application stays fully responsive."},"263":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-18","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#check-indexing-status","content":"Use the stats property to get real-time insights into your collection's indexing state:"},"264":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-19","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#check-indexing-status","content":"doc_count: Total number of documents currently stored."},"265":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-20","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#check-indexing-status","content":"index_completeness: Fraction (0.0~1.0) indicating how much of the vector data has been indexed."},"266":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-21","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#check-indexing-status","content":"1.0 → All vectors for that vector field are fully indexed using the configured index"},"267":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-22","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#check-indexing-status","content":"0.0 → No indexing has occurred; all vectors remain in the flat buffer and are searched via brute force"},"268":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-23","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#check-indexing-status","content":"Values in between → Indexing is partial or in progress"},"269":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-24","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#when-to-call-optimize","content":"Optimize regularly — but not too often:"},"270":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-25","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#when-to-call-optimize","content":"Too infrequent → Flat buffers grow large, degrading search performance"},"271":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-26","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#when-to-call-optimize","content":"Too frequent → Wastes resources optimizing small batches prematurely"},"272":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-27","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#when-to-call-optimize","content":"Find a balance based on your data ingestion rate and query latency requirements."},"273":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-28","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#when-to-call-optimize","content":"className: text-base"},"274":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-29","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#when-to-call-optimize","content":"type: idea"},"275":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize-30","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/optimize","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/optimize#when-to-call-optimize","content":"Best practice:Check your collection's indexing status if searches feel slow.As a general guideline, consider optimizing when you have 100,000+ unindexed documents — but adjust based on your specific use case."},"276":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","type":"page","content":"Schema Evolution","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Working with Data","Collections"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution"},"277":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-0","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#data-definition-language-ddl","content":"Data Definition Language (DDL)"},"278":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-1","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#prerequisites","content":"Prerequisites"},"279":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-2","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#column-ddl","content":"Column DDL"},"280":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-3","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#add-a-column","content":"Add a Column"},"281":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-4","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#drop-a-column","content":"Drop a Column"},"282":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-5","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#alter-a-column","content":"Alter a Column"},"283":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-6","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#view-the-current-schema","content":"View the Current Schema"},"284":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-7","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#index-ddl","content":"Index DDL"},"285":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-8","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#create-an-index","content":"Create an Index"},"286":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-9","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#drop-an-index","content":"Drop an Index"},"287":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-10","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","content":"Zvec supports dynamic schema evolution, allowing you to modify a collection's structure after it has been created — without downtime, data re-ingestion, or reindexing."},"288":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-11","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","content":"You can:"},"289":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-12","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","content":"✅ Add or drop scalar fields"},"290":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-13","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","content":"✅ Rename fields or change their data types ((as long as the change is safe — e.g., from INT32 to INT64)"},"291":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-14","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","content":"✅ Create or drop indexes on fields"},"292":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-15","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","content":"❌  Add or drop vector fields (🔜 coming soon)"},"293":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-16","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#data-definition-language-ddl","content":"In Zvec, schema changes are performed using Data Definition Language (DDL) methods, grouped into two categories:"},"294":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-17","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#data-definition-language-ddl","content":"Column DDL: defines what data you store.It manages the structure of your collection by adding, removing, renaming or altering fields."},"295":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-18","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#data-definition-language-ddl","content":"Index DDL: defines how you search that data.It controls the creation and removal of indexes on fields."},"296":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-19","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#data-definition-language-ddl","content":"className: text-base"},"297":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-20","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#data-definition-language-ddl","content":"type: info"},"298":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-21","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#data-definition-language-ddl","content":"💡 Indexing Rules in Zvec"},"299":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-22","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#data-definition-language-ddl","content":"Every vector field must be indexed using an appropriate vector index to enable similarity search."},"300":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-23","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#data-definition-language-ddl","content":"Scalar fields are optionally indexed — but you should build inverted indexes on any scalar field you plan to use in filtering queries (e.g., WHERE category = 'music')."},"301":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-24","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#prerequisites","content":"This guide assumes you have opened a collection and have a collection object ready."},"302":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-25","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#prerequisites","content":"This example collection includes a scalar field publish_year."},"303":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-26","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#add-a-column","content":"To add a new scalar field to an existing collection, use add_column():"},"304":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-27","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#add-a-column","content":"field_schema:Defines the name and data type of the new field. See scalar field schema for details."},"305":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-28","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#add-a-column","content":"expression:Specifies the default value for existing documents. Since they don't already have a rating field, Zvec uses this expression to fill in the missing values — in this case, setting rating = 5 for all current documents."},"306":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-29","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#add-a-column","content":"className: text-base"},"307":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-30","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#add-a-column","content":"type: info"},"308":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-31","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#add-a-column","content":"Currently, only numerical scalar fields can be added via add_column(). Support for string and boolean types is coming soon.Accordingly, the expression must evaluate to a number — it can be a single numerical literal (like \"5\") or a simple arithmetic expression involving existing numerical fields (e.g., \"publish_year + 1\")."},"309":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-32","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#drop-a-column","content":"To permanently remove a scalar field, use drop_column():"},"310":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-33","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#drop-a-column","content":"className: text-base"},"311":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-34","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#drop-a-column","content":"type: warn"},"312":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-35","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#drop-a-column","content":"This deletes the field and all its data from every document in the collection. The operation is irreversible."},"313":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-36","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#alter-a-column","content":"To rename a column or update its schema, use alter_column():"},"314":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-37","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#view-the-current-schema","content":"After making changes, you can always check your collection's current structure by printing its schema:"},"315":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-38","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#view-the-current-schema","content":"See schema example for more details."},"316":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-39","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#create-an-index","content":"To accelerate search performance, you can create (or replace) indexes on both vector and scalar fields using create_index():"},"317":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-40","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#create-an-index","content":"Vector fields must use one of the following index types:"},"318":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-41","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#create-an-index","content":"HnswIndexParam"},"319":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-42","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#create-an-index","content":"IVFIndexParam"},"320":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-43","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#create-an-index","content":"FlatIndexParam"},"321":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-44","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#create-an-index","content":"Scalar fields use InvertIndexParam to enable efficient filtering."},"322":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-45","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#drop-an-index","content":"To remove an index from a scalar field, use drop_index():"},"323":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-46","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#drop-an-index","content":"className: text-base"},"324":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-47","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#drop-an-index","content":"type: info"},"325":{"id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution-48","page_id":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/collections/schema-evolution#drop-an-index","content":"It is not allowed to drop the index of a vector field.In Zvec, every vector field must always have exactly one index to support similarity search."},"326":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","type":"page","content":"Data Modeling","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Introduction","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling"},"327":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-0","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#collections","content":"Collections"},"328":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-1","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#why-use-collections","content":"Why Use Collections?"},"329":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-2","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#persistence","content":"Persistence"},"330":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-3","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#documents","content":"Documents"},"331":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-4","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#structure-of-a-document","content":"Structure of a Document"},"332":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-5","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#example-document","content":"Example Document"},"333":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-6","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#data-types","content":"Data Types"},"334":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-7","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#scalar-types","content":"Scalar Types"},"335":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-8","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#vector-types","content":"Vector Types"},"336":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-9","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#indexes","content":"Indexes"},"337":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-10","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","content":"In Zvec, data is organized into collections and documents."},"338":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-11","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#collections","content":"A collection is a named container for documents — similar to a table in a relational database system such as MySQL, where each document represents a row in a table. A collection is where you store, organize, and query your data."},"339":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-12","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#collections","content":"Every collection is governed by a schema that defines the scalar fields and vectors it contains, along with their types and indexing settings."},"340":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-13","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#collections","content":"All documents within a collection conform to the same schema."},"341":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-14","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#collections","content":"className: text-base"},"342":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-15","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#collections","content":"type: success"},"343":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-16","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#collections","content":"The schema in Zvec is dynamic: you can add or remove scalar fields and vectors at any time without recreating the collection."},"344":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-17","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#collections","content":"className: text-base"},"345":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-18","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#collections","content":"type: error"},"346":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-19","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#collections","content":"No cross-collection queries: Joins, unions, or multi-collection searches are not supported. Design your data model accordingly."},"347":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-20","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#why-use-collections","content":"Collections provide isolation by ensuring that each data workload operates within its own dedicated schema and indexing configuration. This separation prevents interference between unrelated use cases and allows each to evolve independently."},"348":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-21","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#why-use-collections","content":"For example:"},"349":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-22","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#why-use-collections","content":"A Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) collection might store text embeddings together with metadata — such as title, section, source URL, and last-updated timestamp."},"350":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-23","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#why-use-collections","content":"An image search collection could hold high-dimensional image embeddings along with associated fields like image ID, file path, or caption."},"351":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-24","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#persistence","content":"Each collection is persisted independently on disk in its own dedicated directory, providing isolation between different data workloads."},"352":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-25","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#persistence","content":"Each collection is self-contained within its directory. This means you can relocate a collection's directory and Zvec will still be able to open it when provided with the correct path."},"353":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-26","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#documents","content":"A document is the fundamental unit of data storage — think of it as a single record or row in a relational database table. Each document lives inside a collection and must conform to that collection's schema."},"354":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-27","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#structure-of-a-document","content":"A document is a structured object composed of three core components."},"355":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-28","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#structure-of-a-document","content":"🔑 id: A unique string identifier for the document, cannot be changed after insertion"},"356":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-29","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#structure-of-a-document","content":"📐 vectors: A named set of vectors"},"357":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-30","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#structure-of-a-document","content":"🗂️ fields: A named set of scalar (non-vector) fields, which can include strings, numbers, booleans, or arrays of these types"},"358":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-31","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#example-document","content":"This document belongs to a collection with a schema that defines:"},"359":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-32","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#example-document","content":"Two dense vector: vector_1 (4-dimensional) and vector_2 (6-dimensional)"},"360":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-33","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#example-document","content":"One sparse vector: vector_3"},"361":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-34","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#example-document","content":"Scalar fields: category (string), price (integer), and languages (array of strings)"},"362":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-35","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#example-document","content":"className: text-base"},"363":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-36","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#example-document","content":"type: info"},"364":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-37","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#example-document","content":"All fields must conform to their declared types in the schema. Vectors must exactly match the specified type (dense or sparse) and dimensionality (e.g., a 768-dimensional dense vector cannot accept a 512-dimensional vector)."},"365":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-38","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#example-document","content":"className: text-base"},"366":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-39","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#example-document","content":"type: idea"},"367":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-40","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#example-document","content":"Once inserted, documents can be updated via upsert() or partial update() operations, but all modifications must still adhere to the collection's schema constraints."},"368":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-41","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#data-types","content":"Zvec uses a strongly typed schema system based on the DataType enumeration. The supported types fall into two categories:"},"369":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-42","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#data-types","content":"Scalar types — strings, integers, floats, booleans, and arrays of these types"},"370":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-43","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#data-types","content":"Vector types — dense or sparse numeric representations for vector embeddings"},"371":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-44","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#data-types","content":"className: text-base"},"372":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-45","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#data-types","content":"type: info"},"373":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-46","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#data-types","content":"Type safety is enforced at ingestion: each document field must conform to its corresponding declared DataType."},"374":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-47","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#scalar-types","content":"Elementary Types"},"375":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-48","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"t