a-modeling#vector-types","content":"Dense Vector Types:represented as fixed-length numeric arrays, e.g., [0.1, -0.5, ..., 0.9]"},"396":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-69","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#vector-types","content":"VECTOR_FP16"},"397":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-70","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#vector-types","content":"VECTOR_FP32"},"398":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-71","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#vector-types","content":"VECTOR_INT8"},"399":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-72","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#vector-types","content":"Sparse Vector Types:represented as maps from integer indices to float values, e.g., { 42: 0.85, 1024: 0.13 }"},"400":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-73","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#vector-types","content":"SPARSE_VECTOR_FP32"},"401":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-74","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#vector-types","content":"SPARSE_VECTOR_FP16"},"402":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-75","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#indexes","content":"Indexes accelerate data retrieval beyond basic storage of scalar fields and vectors. In Zvec:"},"403":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-76","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#indexes","content":"Every vector field must be indexed using an appropriate vector index to enable similarity search."},"404":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-77","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#indexes","content":"Scalar fields are optionally indexed — but you should build inverted indexes on any scalar field you plan to use in filtering queries (e.g., WHERE category = 'music')."},"405":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling-78","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/data-modeling#indexes","content":"You can define indexes at collection creation by specifying index_param in the schema for each field or vector.Alternatively, you can add indexes after collection creation by calling create_index() dynamically — no data re-ingestion required."},"406":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts","type":"page","content":"Concepts","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Introduction","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts"},"407":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts-0","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts","content":"This section introduces key terms and foundational ideas that underpin the design and usage of Zvec."},"408":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","type":"page","content":"Inverted Index","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Introduction","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index"},"409":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-0","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#when-to-use-an-inverted-index","content":"When to Use an Inverted Index"},"410":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-1","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#how-does-it-work","content":"How Does It Work?"},"411":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-2","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#why-inverted