[1, 4, 5]"},"485":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-76","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#how-does-it-work","content":"\"Show recipes by Marco Rossi\" → look up \"Marco Rossi\" in the author index → [4, 5]"},"486":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-77","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#how-does-it-work","content":"\"Find Italian recipes by Julia Chen\" → intersect [1, 4, 5] and [1, 6] → [1]"},"487":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-78","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#how-does-it-work","content":"We do not index url, because it's rarely used in queries. Indexing it would waste storage and slow down writes, with little benefit. Once we have a document ID, we can always fetch its url directly from the original data."},"488":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-79","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#why-inverted","content":"Because it inverts the standard mapping:"},"489":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-80","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#why-inverted","content":"Direction"},"490":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-81","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#why-inverted","content":"Mapping"},"491":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-82","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#why-inverted","content":"Forward"},"492":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-83","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#why-inverted","content":"Document ID → List of Terms"},"493":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-84","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#why-inverted","content":"Inverted"},"494":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-85","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#why-inverted","content":"Term → List of Document IDs"},"495":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-86","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#why-inverted","content":"This inversion is what makes keyword-based search efficient. Instead of checking every document to see if it contains your query term, you jump straight to the term and get all matching documents immediately."},"496":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-87","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#trade-offs","content":"While powerful, inverted indexes come with costs:"},"497":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-88","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#trade-offs","content":"⚠️ Storage overhead: The index requires additional storage space."},"498":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index-89","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/inverted-index#trade-offs","content":"⚠️ Write amplification: Every write operation — INSERT, UPSERT, and UPDATE — require index maintenance, which adds latency to writes and increases I/O load."},"499":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","type":"page","content":"Vector Embedding","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Introduction","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding"},"500":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-0","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#what-is-a-vector","content":"What is a Vector?"},"501":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-1","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#how-do-you-use-vectors-with-a-database","content":"How Do You Use Vectors with a Database?"},"502":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-2","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#how-vectors-power-real-world-applications","content":"How Vectors Power Real-World Applications?"},"503":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-3","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#what-is-an-embedding-model","content":"What is an Embedding Model?"},"504":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-4","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#types-of-vectors","content":"Types of Vectors"},"505":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-5","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#dense-vectors","content":"Dense Vectors"},"506":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-6","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#sparse-vectors","content":"Sparse Vectors"},"507":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-7","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#what-is-a-vector","content":"In the context of AI and vector databases, a vector is a list of numbers generated by embedding models to capture the semantic essence of unstructured data —  such as text, images, or audio."},"508":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-8","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#what-is-a-vector","content":"These models transform raw input into a high-dimensional space where semantically similar items produce similar vectors, enabling AI systems to compare meaning rather than relying on exact word matches."},"509":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-9","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#how-do-you-use-vectors-with-a-database","content":"🗂️ Store: Generate embeddings from your data — documents, product images, or user profiles — and save them in the vector database."},"510":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-10","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#how-do-you-use-vectors-with-a-database","content":"🔍 Search: When a new query arrives (a question, photo, etc.), generate a query vector using the same embedding model, then ask the database to find the most similar stored vectors."},"511":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-11","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#how-do-you-use-vectors-with-a-database","content":"Using efficient indexes, the database quickly returns relevant results — even at large scale. This is the foundation of semantic search: finding what means the same, not just what says the same."},"512":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-12","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#how-vectors-power-real-world-applications","content":"Image search is a great example:"},"513":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-13","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#how-vectors-power-real-world-applications","content":"Each image is converted into a vector that captures its visual features — such as shape, color, and object type."},"514":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-14","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#how-vectors-power-real-world-applications","content":"Images that are visually or semantically similar end up with nearby vectors."},"515":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-15","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#how-vectors-power-real-world-applications","content":"By comparing these vectors, systems can:"},"516":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-16","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#how-vectors-power-real-world-applications","content":"✅ Recognize the same person across different photos: Even with changes in lighting, pose, or expression, images of one individual generate similar vectors, allowing the system to match identities reliably."},"517":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-17","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#how-vectors-power-real-world-applications","content":"✅ Find look-alike products in e-commerce: When a user snaps a photo of a dress, lamp, or sofa, the system compares its vector to product vectors and retrieves items with similar appearance or style."},"518":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-18","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#how-vectors-power-real-world-applications","content":"All of this happens through fast vector similarity comparisons, powered by the vector database."},"519":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-19","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#what-is-an-embedding-model","content":"An embedding model is an AI model that converts raw data into vector embeddings — illustrated in the diagram at the top."},"520":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-20","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#what-is-an-embedding-model","content":"These models learn patterns from vast amounts of training data so that objects with similar meanings produce vectors that are close together in vector space — typically measured using distance metrics such as cosine similarity, dot product, or Euclidean distance."},"521":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-21","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#what-is-an-embedding-model","content":"className: text-base"},"522":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-22","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#what-is-an-embedding-model","content":"type: info"},"523":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-23","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#what-is-an-embedding-model","content":"The choice of distance metric matters. If an embedding model was trained for a specific metric (e.g., cosine similarity), the vector database should use the same metric during search to preserve semantic relationships and achieve optimal accuracy."},"524":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-24","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#what-is-an-embedding-model","content":"To explore and compare state-of-the-art embedding models, you can check out the Embedding Leaderboard on Hugging Face, which evaluates hundreds of models across diverse tasks and languages."},"525":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-25","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#types-of-vectors","content":"Vector representations are primarily categorized into two types: dense and sparse, each capturing data in its own way."},"526":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-26","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#dense-vectors","content":"Dense vectors are fixed-length, real-valued embeddings where (nearly) every dimension carries semantic information. These vectors are often generated by deep learning models that transform raw inputs (e.g., text, images, audio) into a structured vector space reflecting their semantic similarities."},"527":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-27","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#dense-vectors","content":"✅ Semantic-Rich: understands context and meaning (e.g., \"king – man + woman ≈ queen\")"},"528":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-28","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#dense-vectors","content":"⚠️ Opaque: hard to interpret which features drive similarity"},"529":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-29","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#sparse-vectors","content":"Sparse vectors are high-dimensional, often vocabulary-sized representations in which only a small subset of dimensions are non-zero. Each active dimension corresponds to a specific term (e.g., a word or n-gram), weighted by relevance scores such as BM25."},"530":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-30","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#sparse-vectors","content":"In this model, every document is converted into a vector — called a document vector — that records which terms appear in it and how important they are. Similarly, a search query is also turned into a sparse vector using the same weighting scheme."},"531":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-31","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#sparse-vectors","content":"Rather than relying on exact keyword matches, similarity between a query and a document is computed using the dot product of their vectors. This measures how well their weighted terms align: documents that contain the same important terms as the query receive higher scores — rewarding both term overlap and term importance."},"532":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-32","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#sparse-vectors","content":"For computational efficiency, sparse vectors use integer indices to map terms to their positions within a vocabulary dictionary rather than storing the term strings directly."},"533":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-33","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#sparse-vectors","content":"✅ Interpretable: non-zero dimensions map directly to known terms (e.g., 4017 → \"puppy\")"},"534":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding-34","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-embedding#sparse-vectors","content":"⚠️ Lacks Semantic Understanding: treats \"car\" and \"automobile\" as unrelated unless explicitly linked"},"535":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","type":"page","content":"Delete","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Working with Data","Data Operations"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete"},"536":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-0","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete#delete-by-ids","content":"Delete by IDs"},"537":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-1","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete#delete-by-filter-condition","content":"Delete by Filter Condition"},"538":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-2","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"Zvec provides two ways to delete documents. Choose the method that best fits your use case:"},"539":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-3","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"Method"},"540":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-4","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"Input"},"541":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-5","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"When to Use"},"542":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-6","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"delete()"},"543":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-7","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"One or more document ids"},"544":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-8","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"Use when you know the exact ID(s) of the documents you want to delete"},"545":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-9","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"delete_by_filter()"},"546":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-10","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"A filter expression (e.g., publish_year < 1900)"},"547":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-11","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"Use for bulk deletion based on field values — ideal for cleaning up documents that match specific criteria"},"548":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-12","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"className: text-base"},"549":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-13","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"type: warn"},"550":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-14","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","content":"Delete operations are immediate and irreversible.Always double-check your input before running a delete operation."},"551":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-15","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete#delete-by-ids","content":"Assume you've already opened a collection and have a collection object ready."},"552":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-16","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete#delete-by-ids","content":"Use delete() to remove one or more documents when you know their exact IDs."},"553":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-17","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete#delete-by-ids","content":"className: text-base"},"554":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-18","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete#delete-by-ids","content":"type: info"},"555":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-19","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete#delete-by-ids","content":"When given a single id, delete() returns one Status object."},"556":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-20","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete#delete-by-ids","content":"When given a list of ids, it returns a list of Status objects in the same order."},"557":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-21","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete#delete-by-ids","content":"{\"code\": 0} indicates success."},"558":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-22","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete#delete-by-ids","content":"Non-zero codes indicate failure — for example, if the document id does not exist."},"559":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-23","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete#delete-by-filter-condition","content":"Use delete_by_filter() to remove all documents that match a boolean filter expression."},"560":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete-24","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/delete#delete-by-filter-condition","content":"The filter can reference scalar fields (e.g., publish_year, language) using comparison and logical operators."},"561":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/fetch","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/fetch","type":"page","content":"Fetch","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Working with Data","Data Operations"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/fetch"},"562":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/fetch-0","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/fetch","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/data-operations/fetch","content":"Use fetch() to retrieve documents by their ids.This is a direct lookup — no search, scoring, or filtering is involved."},"563":{"id":"/en/docs/data-o