 memory usage"},"750":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-9","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"HNSW builds a multi-layer graph structure where each node represents a vector and edges connect nodes based on similarity."},"751":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-10","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Layers form a hierarchy 🪜"},"752":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-11","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Upper layers are sparse and act as \"highways\" for fast long-range navigation."},"753":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-12","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Lower layers are dense and provide fine-grained local neighborhood connectivity."},"754":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-13","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"How search works (coarse → fine) 🔍"},"755":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-14","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Start from an entry point at the top layer."},"756":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-15","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"At the current layer, you greedily walk to neighbors that are closer to the query vector, until you can't get any closer."},"757":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-16","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Then you drop down one layer at that position and repeat the same greedy search."},"758":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-17","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"On the lowest layer, this process is done more carefully (with a small candidate list) to refine the result."},"759":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-18","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Why this is fast and accurate ⚡ 🎯"},"760":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-19","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Fast: Upper layers let you jump quickly to the right region without visiting most points."},"761":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-20","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Accurate: The dense bottom layer lets you explore the local neighborhood thoroughly, so recall stays high."},"762":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-21","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#when-to-use-an-hnsw-index","content":"✅ Real-time, low-latency applications (e.g., conversational AI and live recommendations)"},"763":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-22","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#when-to-use-an-hnsw-index","content":"✅ Production systems requiring consistent high recall with minimal latency"},"764":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-23","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#when-to-use-an-hnsw-index","content":"className: text-base"},"765":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-24","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#when-to-use-an-hnsw-index","content":"type: idea"},"766":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-25","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#when-to-use-an-hnsw-index","content":"Best Practice: HNSW is our recommended default for most production use cases. It strikes an excellent balance between speed, accuracy, and robustness."},"767":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-26","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#advantages","content":"✨ Near-logarithmic query time — Typically O(log n) for large datasets"},"768":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-27","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#advantages","content":"✨ Consistently high recall across diverse data distributions"},"769":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-28","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#advantages","content":"✨ Faster indexing than many alternatives (e.g., IVF-based methods)"},"770":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-29","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#trade-offs","content":"⚠️ Higher memory footprint — Graph links require additional storage (scales with m)"},"771":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-30","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#trade-offs","content":"⚠️ Indexing complexity of O(n log n) — Slower build time than Flat index (but often faster than IVF)"},"772":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-31","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#key-parameters","content":"className: text-base"},"773":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-32","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#key-parameters","content":"type: idea"},"774":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-33","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#key-parameters","content":"Tuning Tip:Start with defaults, then adjust ef first for recall/latency trade-offs.Only if needed, increase ef_construction or m for better accuracy — but expect slower indexing and higher memory use."},"775":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-34","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Parameter"},"776":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-35","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Description"},"777":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-36","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Tuning Guidance"},"778":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-37","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"metric_type"},"779":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-38","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Similarity metric used to compare vectors"},"780":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-39","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Choose based on how your embeddings were trained"},"781":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-40","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"m"},"782":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-41","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Max neighbors per node — The maximum number of bidirectional links created for each node during graph construction"},"783":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-42","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"• Higher m →  ✨ better recall and graph connectivity  ⚠️ more memory usage and higher latency for both indexing and search"},"784":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-43","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"ef_construction"},"785":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-44","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Index-time candidate pool size — Determines how many neighboring candidates the algorithm considers when inserting a new vector into the graph"},"786":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-45","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"• Higher ef_construction →  ✨ better graph quality and higher recall  ⚠️ longer index build time (does not affect query speed)"},"787":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-46","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"quantize_type"},"788":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-47","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Vector quantization method to apply  Defaults to no quantization"},"789":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-48","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"See Quantization for more details"},"790":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-49","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Parameter"},"791":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-50","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Description"},"792":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-51","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Tuning Guidance"},"793":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-52","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"ef"},"794":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-53","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Query-time candidate pool size — Determines how many potential neighbors are explored at each step during graph traversal at query time"},"795":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-54","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"• Higher ef →  ✨ higher recall  ⚠️ higher query latency"},"796":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-55","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"radius"},"797":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-56","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Distance (similarity) threshold for range-based filtering — only documents satisfying the threshold are returned"},"798":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-57","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Example:  • With inner product MetricType.IP, set radius=0.6 to  keep only results with score > 0.6  ✅ Use when: You want to filter out low-quality matches  🚫 Skip when: You want all top-k results, regardless of quality"},"799":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-58","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"is_linear"},"800":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-59","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Forces a brute-force linear search instead of using the index"},"801":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-60","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"🐌 Very slow for large datasets!  ✅ Only use for: Debugging, tiny collections, or verifying index accuracy"},"802":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-61","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"is_using_refiner"},"803":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-62","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Enables exact score refinement (recomputes exact similarity scores) for top candidates — useful when vectors are quantized"},"804":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-63","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"✅ Turn on: When you need higher accuracy  ⚠️ Adds latency due to exact re-scoring"},"805":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","type":"page","content":"Vector Index","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Introduction","Concepts","Vector Index"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index"},"806":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-0","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#approximate-vs-exact-search","content":"Approximate vs. Exact Search"},"807":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-1","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"Recall: Measuring Approximation Quality"},"808":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-2","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"Vector Index Types"},"809":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-3","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","content":"A vector index is a specialized data structure that accelerates similarity search over large collections of vector embeddings."},"810":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-4","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","content":"Without an index, finding the most similar items to a query requires comparing it against every single vector in the database — a process known as brute-force or flat search."},"811":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-5","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","content":"Brute-force search is:"},"812":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-6","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","content":"✅ Accurate: Returns the exact most similar results — no approximation."},"813":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-7","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","content":"⚠️ Painfully slow at scale: With millions or billions of vectors, queries can take seconds or minutes, making them impractical for real-time applications."},"814":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-8","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#approximate-vs-exact-search","content":"Most vector indexes use Approximate Nearest Neighbor (ANN) algorithms."},"815":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-9","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#approximate-vs-exact-search","content":"Instead of finding the exact closest matches, ANN finds very close approximations — often indistinguishable in quality for practical purposes — while delivering massive gains in speed and efficiency."},"816":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-10","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#approximate-vs-exact-search","content":"For real-world uses, such as semantic search or recommendations, this small accuracy trade-off delivers huge gains in speed and scalability. In short: good enough to be correct, but lightning fast ✨."},"817":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-11","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"Recall is the standard metric for evaluating how well an ANN algorithm preserves result quality."},"818":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-12","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"It quantifies the fraction of true nearest neighbors — identified by an exact (brute-force) search — that appear in the top‑k results returned by the approximate method:"},"819":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-13","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"Example:"},"820":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-14","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"If you request the top 10 results and 9 of them match the true top 10 from a brute-force search, your recall@10 is 90%."},"821":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-15","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"High recall (e.g., ≥ 96%) typically means the approximation is practically indistinguishable from exact search for most applications."},"822":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-16","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"Different index types (e.g., HNSW) and their parameters (e.g., ef_search) let you fine-tune the balance between recall, query speed, and resource usage — so you can optimize for your specific accuracy and performance requirements."},"823":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-17","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"Zvec supports three vector index types, each suited to different use cases, dataset sizes, and performance requirements:"},"824":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-18","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"Flat (Brute-Force) index"},"825":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-19","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"HNSW (Hierarchical Navigable Small World)"},"826":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-20","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"IVF (Inverted File Index)"},"827":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-21","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"className: text-base"},"828":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-22","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"type: idea"},"829":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-23","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"Choose an index type based on your scale, latency requirements, and accuracy tolerance. Always use the same distance metric that your embedding model was trained for."},"830":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"page","content":"IVF Index","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Introduction","Concepts","Vector Index"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index"},"831":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-0","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","content":"Inverted File Index"},"832":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-1","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#how-it-works","content":"How It Works"},"833":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-2","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#indexing-phase-️","content":"Indexing Phase ⚙️"},"834":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-3","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-phase-","content":"Query Phase 🔍"},"835":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-4","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"When to Use an IVF Index"},"836":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-5","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#advantages","content":"Advantages"},"837":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-6","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#trade-offs","content":"Trade-offs"},"838":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-7","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#key-parameters","content":"Key Parameters"},"839":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-8","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Index-Time Parameters"},"840":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-9","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Query-Time Parameters"},"841":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-10","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","content":"A partition-based, scalable, memory-efficient indexing method best suited for large datasets — especially those with natural cluster structure — at the expense of slower indexing and more involved tuning"},"842":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-11","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#how-it-works","content":"IVF operates by partitioning the entire vector space into clusters. The number of clusters is controlled by the parameter n_list (short for \"number of lists\")."},"843":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-12","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#indexing-phase-️","content":"Clustering: The algorithm first applies a clustering algorithm, creating n_list clusters. Each cluster is represented by its centroid — a central point that best represents all vectors assigned to that cluster."},"844":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-13","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#indexing-phase-️","content":"Assignment: Each vector in the dataset is assigned to the cluster whose centroid is closest to it. The vector is then stored in an inverted list (also called a \"bucket\") associated with that centroid. The index essentially becomes a mapping from centroids to their associated vectors."},"845":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-14","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-phase-","content":"Centroid Selection: When a query vector arrives, the system first computes distances between the query and all n_list centroids to identify the n_probe nearest centroids (n_probe is a parameter that controls how many centroids to consider)."},"846":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-15","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-phase-","content":"Local Search: Instead of scanning the entire dataset of N vectors, the search is restricted to only the vectors stored in the n_probe selected buckets. A brute-force (or refined) search is then performed within those buckets to find the final nearest neighbors."},"847":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-16","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"✅ Your vector dataset exhibits natural clustering or locality structure"},"848":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-17","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"✅ You’re working with very large datasets and memory efficiency is critical"},"849":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-18","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"✅ You need to tune parameters to achieve optimal performance"},"850":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-19","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"className: text-base"},"851":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-20","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"type: idea"},"852":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-21","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"Best Practice:"},"853":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-22","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"IVF works best on datasets with inherent clustering structure."},"854":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-23","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"For even greater memory efficiency and scalability, combine it with Product Quantization (PQ)."},"855":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-24","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"The performance of IVF is highly sensitive to parameters like n_list. As such, IVF is best suited for practitioners who can systematically experiment with, validate, and optimize these settings for their specific data distribution and latency-recall requirements."},"856":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-25","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#advantages","content":"✨ Compatibility — Often used as a base layer in composite indexes (e.g., IVF-PQ) for further optimization"},"857":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-26","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#advantages","content":"✨ Scalability — Query time scales approximately as O(N / n_list × n_probe), making it highly efficient for large N when n_list is large and n_probe is small"},"858":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-27","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#advantages","content":"✨ Memory Efficiency — Stores vectors in compact inverted lists with minimal overhead from centroids and list pointers, typically uses significantly less memory than graph-based methods like HNSW"},"859":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-28","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#trade-offs","content":"⚠️ Indexing Overhead — Building the index requires clustering, which can be computationally intensive and slower to build than indexes like HNSW"},"860":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-29","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#trade-offs","content":"⚠️ Parameter Sensitivity — Accuracy and latency are highly dependent on the choice of n_list and n_probe"},"861":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-30","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Parameter"},"862":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-31","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Description"},"863":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-32","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Tuning Guidance"},"864":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-33","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"metric_type"},"865":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-34","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Similarity metric used to compare vectors"},"866":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-35","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Choose based on how your embeddings were trained"},"867":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-36","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"n_list"},"868":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-37","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Number of clusters (inverted lists) — the vector space is partitioned into this many clusters during indexing"},"869":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-38","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"• Start with n_list ≈ \\sqrt{N}, where N is the number of vectors  • Larger n_list → ✨ finer partitioning, smaller buckets, faster search — but ⚠️ higher indexing cost and more centroids to manage  • Smaller n_list → ✨ faster index construction — but ⚠️ larger buckets and slower search"},"870":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-39","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"n_iters"},"871":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-40","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Centroid refinement iterations — number of passes to optimize cluster centroids during indexing"},"872":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-41","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"• Higher n_iters →  ✨ better clustering quality  ⚠️ longer index build time"},"873":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-42","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"quantize_type"},"874":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-43","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Vector quantization method to apply  Defaults to no quantization"},"875":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-44","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"See Quantization for more details"},"876":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-45","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Parameter"},"877":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-46","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Description"},"878":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-47","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Tuning Guidance"},"879":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-48","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"n_probe"},"880":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-49","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Number of clusters to search at query time — the system retrieves candidates only from these nearest clusters."},"881":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-50","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"• Higher n_probe →  ✨ higher recall  ⚠️ slower queries"},"882":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-51","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"radius"},"883":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-52","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Distance (similarity) threshold for range-based filtering — only documents satisfying the threshold are returned"},"884":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-53","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Example: With inner product metric MetricType.IP, set radius=0.6 to  keep only results with score > 0.6  ✅ Use when: You want to filter out low-quality matches  🚫 Skip when: You want all top-k results, regardless of quality"},"885":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-54","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"is_linear"},"886":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-55","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Forces a brute-force linear search instead of using the index"},"887":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-56","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"🐌 Very slow for large datasets!  ✅ Only use for: Debugging, tiny collections, or verifying index accuracy"},"888":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"page","content":"Quantization","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Introduction","Concepts","Vector Index"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization"},"889":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-0","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#storage-behavior","content":"Storage Behavior"},"890":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-1","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#enabling-quantization","content":"Enabling Quantization"},"891":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-2","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#quantization-types","content":"Quantization Types"},"892":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-3","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#fp16-half-precision-floating-point","content":"FP16 (Half-Precision Floating Point)"},"893":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-4","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#int8-8-bit-integer-quantization","content":"INT8 (8-Bit Integer Quantization)"},"894":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-5","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#int4-4-bit-integer-quantization","content":"INT4 (4-Bit Integer Quantization)"},"895":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-6","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"Quantization is a compression technique that transforms vectors from their original (specifically FP32) format into a more compact representation, reducing the size of vector indexes used for search."},"896":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-7","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"This transformation approximates vectors using fewer bits per dimension — enabling:"},"897":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-8","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"✨ Lower memory footprint — especially when the index is memory-resident,"},"898":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-9","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"✨ Faster I/O and lower query latency — due to reduced data movement and efficient integer/fp16 arithmetic,"},"899":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-10","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"✨ Better scalability on resource-constrained hardware."},"900":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-11","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"className: text-base"},"901":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-12","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"type: warn"},"902":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-13","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"Important:"},"903":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-14","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"Quantization is a lossy and irreversible compression method. It improves runtime efficiency at the cost of potentially reduced recall accuracy. Always validate its effect on your retrieval quality."},"904":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-15","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"Quantization only provides benefits when applied to vectors in a FP32 format."},"905":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-16","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#storage-behavior","content":"To ensure data integrity and flexibility, Zvec stores both the original vectors and their quantized versions. This means:"},"906":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-17","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#storage-behavior","content":"The overall on-disk storage usage may increase (due to storing two copies)."},"907":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-18","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#storage-behavior","content":"However, only the quantized vectors are loaded into memory for indexing and search, significantly reducing the active index size."},"908":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-19","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#storage-behavior","content":"Users can always retrieve the original, unaltered vectors when needed."},"909":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-20","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#enabling-quantization","content":"You can activate quantization when creating a vector index in Zvec by specifying the desired quantization type (FP16, INT8, or INT4) through the quantize_type parameter in your VectorSchema."},"910":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-21","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#enabling-quantization","content":"Zvec will then automatically generate and manage the quantized representation alongside your original vectors."},"911":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-22","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#fp16-half-precision-floating-point","content":"Uses 16-bit floating-point numbers to reduce memory footprint and accelerate computation while maintaining high numerical precision. Ideal for applications requiring near-FP32 accuracy with improved efficiency. Requires conversion from FP32 source."},"912":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-23","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#int8-8-bit-integer-quantization","content":"Represents vectors using 8-bit integers, significantly reducing storage and memory bandwidth requirements. Offers a good trade-off between speed, size, and retrieval accuracy for many similarity search tasks. Requires conversion from FP32 source."},"913":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-24","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#int4-4-bit-integer-quantization","content":"Ultra-compact representation using only 4 bits per dimension. Maximizes storage density and inference speed, suitable for latency-sensitive or resource-constrained environments where noticeable accuracy loss is acceptable. Requires conversion from FP32 source."},"914":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"page","content":"Conditional Filtering","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Working with Data","Data Operations","Query"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter"},"915":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter-0","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter#performance-considerations","content":"Performance Considerations"},"916":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter-1","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter#prerequisites","content":"Prerequisites"},"917":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter-2","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter#performing-conditional-filtering","content":"Performing Conditional Filtering"},"918":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter-3","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter#supported-filter-syntax","content":"Supported Filter Syntax"},"919":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter-4","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter#comparison-operators","content":"Comparison Operators"},"920":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter-5","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter#membership-operators","content":"Membership Operators"},"921":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter-6","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"heading","tags":[],